rlm-git-squash-branch

Squash every commit on the current branch since the merge base with the
target branch into a single signed-off commit.

The target branch is the base branch of the current PR (resolved via
`gh pr view --json baseRefName`) if one exists, otherwise origin's
default branch (`git symbolic-ref --short refs/remotes/origin/HEAD`,
with `git remote show origin` as fallback). The target is always
referenced as `origin/<branch>`.

Steps:

  1. `git fetch --all` so the target reflects what's on the remote now.
  2. Save the messages of all commits in `merge_base..HEAD`, oldest
     first, in `git merge --squash` shape (one `* <subject>` + body
     block per commit).
  3. `git reset <target>` (mixed) — moves HEAD to the target branch tip
     and leaves the diff in the working tree.
  4. `git add -A` to stage everything.
  5. `git commit -s -e -F -` with the saved messages piped in as the
     initial editor buffer, so the user can edit or accept the combined
     message (or abort by emptying the buffer).

Refuses to run when:
  - HEAD is detached,
  - the working tree is dirty,
  - the current branch is the target branch itself,
  - HEAD is already at the target tip (nothing to squash),
  - reset leaves no staged changes (nothing to squash).

After the commit succeeds, prints the publish commands:

    git push --force-with-lease

  (or, when the remote branch doesn't yet exist:)

    git push -u origin <current-branch>

`--force-with-lease` is used rather than `--force` so the push aborts
if someone else pushed to the same branch in the meantime.

REQUIRES
  git
  gh (optional — only used to detect a PR base branch)
